Task: Dynamic Game Board & Screen Management
Import Custom Components (from Tlacitko import Tlacitko)

Description: Linked the main application with your previously created module. This allows for code reusability—you instantiate the exact same counter logic (Tlacitko) as many times as needed within the app.

Implement Grid Layout (QGridLayout)

Description: Utilized a grid system to organize the players' UI. A grid allows elements to be arranged in rows and columns, making it the ideal choice for displaying multiple counters side-by-side (e.g., in a 2x2 or 3x2 formation).

Automatic Positioning Algorithm (radek = i // 2, sloupec = i % 2)

Description: Used integer division (//) and the modulo operator (%) to automatically calculate each widget's position. This ensures the player counters dynamically wrap into exactly two columns, no matter how many players are selected.

Dynamic Component Initialization with Parameters

Description: Ran a for loop to create a new Tlacitko instance for each player. Passed specific arguments immediately upon creation, including a unique color from a predefined list and the total number of players (to correctly set the starting health to 20 or 40).

Screen Navigation (setCurrentWidget)

Description: Triggered a layer swap within the QStackedWidget. Once the game board is fully built, it is brought to the front, creating a seamless transition from the main menu directly into the active game state.

Return to Menu Functionality (btn_zpet)

Description: Implemented a UI control to exit the current session. This involved creating a "Back to Menu" button and linking it to logic that will reset the view back to the initial player-selection screen.
